-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Diamond Bank, KenolKobil, Naiade, Zenith Bank
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-07-21T16:11:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/sub-saharan-african-stocks-diamond-bank-kenolkobil-naiade-zenith-bank.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  climbed for
a second day, rising 0.3 percent to close at 1,697.68 at 1:30
p.m. in Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  fell 0.7 percent to close at 75.59
as of 2:05 p.m. in Nairobi, the lowest level since July 14. The
 Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  gained for a second day,
advancing 0.6 percent to 254,963.99 according to its website,
while Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  rose for the first
day in six, gaining 2 percent to 768.72.  
 The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  retreated for a
second day, falling 0.3 percent to 6,249.14.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Diamond Bank Plc  (DIAMONDB NL), gained 10 kobo, or 1.4
percent, to 7.30 naira. The company returned to profit in the
first half through June. Net income was 4.59 billion naira
($30.5 million) after a loss of 8.23 billion naira a year
earlier, the company said in a statement e-mailed by the
Nigerian Stock Exchange after the market closed yesterday.  
 KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in seven African nations, dropped for a fourth day,
falling 25 cents, or 2.4 percent, to 10.05 shillings. Kenya’s
Energy Ministry told Kenya Petroleum Refineries Ltd. to release
fuel stock belonging to KenolKobil, Chairman  Jacob Segman  said
in an e-mailed statement today. The refining company has held
the stock since July 13.  
 Naiade Resorts Ltd.  (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
gained 1 rupee, or 3.9 percent, to 27 rupees, the strongest
level since June 7. The company said it will delay a rights
issue planned for this month as it is considering using other
financial instruments, according to a statement published on the
Stock Exchange of Mauritius’s website after the market closed
yesterday.  
 Zenith Bank Plc  (ZENITHBA NL), Nigeria’s third-biggest bank
by market value, gained 10 kobo, or 0.8 percent, to 12.5 naira.
Profit for the first half through June more than doubled to 21.3
billion naira from a year earlier, the bank said in a statement
e-mailed by the Lagos-based Nigerian Stock Exchange today.  
